1297–Female":"1297–Deceased","1302–Male":"1302–Deceased","1311–1356":"1311–1356","1300–Female":"1300–Deceased","1335–1376":"1335–1376","1265–1321":"1265–1321","1330–Female":"1330–Deceased","1330":"1330","1297":"1297","1286":"1286","15 February 1357":"15 February 1356","1284":"1284","1282":"1282","1291":"1291","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","abt 1334":"about 1334","1335":"1335","1302":"1302","1279":"1279","1356":"1356","1311":"1311","1300":"1300","1321":"1321","1376":"1376","1265":"1265","about 1335":"about 1335","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Picton, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wogan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh, English, and Irish (Dublin): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Guoccaun</i>, which derives from the ancestor of Modern Welsh <i>gogawn</i> ‘honour, glory’. In Middle Welsh it became <i>Gwogon</i> and <i>Gwogan</i> and was adopted as a surname by a south Pembrokeshire Anglo-Norman family in the normanized or Anglicized pronunciation <i>Wogan</i>. Compare   Cadogan  . In Ireland the name has been Gaelicized as <b>Úgán</b>.","History: A family of this name settled in County Kildare following the Anglo-Norman invasion of the 12th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ogan","meanings":["Irish: of Welsh origin, a variant of   Wogan  , found Gaelicized as <b>Úgán</b>."]},{"name":"Vogan","meanings":["Irish: of Welsh origin, a variant of   Wogan  ."]},{"name":"Cadogan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot.","Welsh (Pembrokeshire and Glamorgan) and Irish (of Welsh origin): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Catgucaun</i>, <i>Catguocawn</i>, modernized as <i>Cadwgon</i>. It is composed of <i>cad</i> ‘battle’ + <i>gogawn</i> ‘honour, glory’. See also   Wogan  . The surname is stressed, like its Welsh original, on the penultimate syllable, hence its occasional development to   Duggan  .","Irish: from <b>Ó Ceadagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Ceadagán</i>’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Wogan was born in 1311, in Picton, Pembrokeshire, Wales, his father, John Wogan, was 46 and his mother, Joan Picton, was -19. He married Margaret Ivethorn about 1334. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 15 February 1356, in Wales, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1311–15 February 1357":"1311–15. veebruar 1356","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1282–Female":"1282–Surnud","1284–Male":"1284–Surnud","1286–Female":"1286–Surnud","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","1291–Male":"1291–Surnud","1297–Female":"1297–Surnud","1302–Male":"1302–Surnud","1311–1356":"1311–1356","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1335–1376":"1335–1376","1265–1321":"1265–1321","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1330":"1330","1297":"1297","1286":"1286","15 February 1357":"15. veebruar 1356","1284":"1284","1282":"1282","1291":"1291","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","abt 1334":"umbes 1334","1335":"1335","1302":"1302","1279":"1279","1356":"1356","1311":"1311","1300":"1300","1321":"1321","1376":"1376","1265":"1265","about 1335":"umbes 1335","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Picton, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1311–15 February 1357":"1311–15. helmikuuta 1356","1280–Female":"1280–Kuollut","1282–Female":"1282–Kuollut","1284–Male":"1284–Kuollut","1286–Female":"1286–Kuollut","1290–Male":"1290–Kuollut","1291–Male":